# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: diameter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:diameter/4-polytope] In geometry, a **4-polytope** (sometimes also called a **polychoron**, **polycell**, or **polyhedroid**) is a four-dimensional polytope.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] It is a connected and closed figure, composed of lower-dimensional polytopal elements: vertices, edges, faces (polygons), and cells (polyhedra).
[src:diameter/4-polytope] Each face is shared by exactly two cells.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] The 4-polytopes were discovered by the Swiss mathematician Ludwig Schläfli before 1853.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] The two-dimensional analogue of a 4-polytope is a polygon, and the three-dimensional analogue is a polyhedron.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] Topologically 4-polytopes are closely related to the uniform honeycombs, such as the cubic honeycomb, which tessellate 3-space; similarly the 3D cube is related to the infinite 2D square tiling.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] Convex 4-polytopes can be *cut and unfolded* as nets in 3-space.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] A 4-polytope is a closed four-dimensional figure.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] It comprises vertices (corner points), edges, faces and cells.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] A cell is the three-dimensional analogue of a face, and is therefore a polyhedron.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] Each face must join exactly two cells, analogous to the way in which each edge of a polyhedron joins just two faces.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] Like any polytope, the elements of a 4-polytope cannot be subdivided into two or more sets which are also 4-polytopes, i.e. it is not a compound.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] The convex regular 4-polytopes are the four-dimensional analogues of the Platonic solids.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] The most familiar 4-polytope is the tesseract or hypercube, the 4D analogue of the cube.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] The convex regular 4-polytopes can be ordered by size as a measure of 4-dimensional content (hypervolume) for the same radius.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] Each greater polytope in the sequence is *rounder* than its predecessor, enclosing more content within the same radius.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] The 4-simplex (5-cell) is the limit smallest case, and the 120-cell is the largest.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] Complexity (as measured by comparing configuration matrices or simply the number of vertices) follows the same ordering.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] 4-polytopes cannot be seen in three-dimensional space due to their extra dimension.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] Several techniques are used to help visualise them.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] Orthogonal projections can be used to show various symmetry orientations of a 4-polytope.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] They can be drawn in 2D as vertex-edge graphs, and can be shown in 3D with solid faces as visible projective envelopes.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] Just as a 3D shape can be projected onto a flat sheet, so a 4-D shape can be projected onto 3-space or even onto a flat sheet.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] One common projection is a Schlegel diagram which uses stereographic projection of points on the surface of a 3-sphere into three dimensions, connected by straight edges, faces, and cells drawn in 3-space.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] Just as a slice through a polyhedron reveals a cut surface, so a slice through a 4-polytope reveals a cut "hypersurface" in three dimensions.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] A sequence of such sections can be used to build up an understanding of the overall shape.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] The extra dimension can be equated with time to produce a smooth animation of these cross sections.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] A net of a 4-polytope is composed of polyhedral cells that are connected by their faces and all occupy the same three-dimensional space, just as the polygon faces of a net of a polyhedron are connected by their edges and all occupy the same plane.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] The topology of any given 4-polytope is defined by its Betti numbers and torsion coefficients.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] The value of the Euler characteristic used to characterise polyhedra does not generalize usefully to higher dimensions, and is zero for all 4-polytopes, whatever their underlying topology.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] This inadequacy of the Euler characteristic to reliably distinguish between different topologies in higher dimensions led to the discovery of the more sophisticated Betti numbers.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] Similarly, the notion of orientability of a polyhedron is insufficient to characterise the surface twistings of toroidal 4-polytopes, and this led to the use of torsion coefficients.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] Like all polytopes, 4-polytopes may be classified based on properties like "convexity" and "symmetry".
[src:diameter/4-polytope] These categories include only the 4-polytopes that exhibit a high degree of symmetry.
[src:diameter/4-polytope] Many other 4-polytopes are possible, but they have not been studied as extensively as the ones included in these categories.
[src:diameter/5-cell] In geometry, the **5-cell** is the convex 4-polytope with Schläfli symbol {3,3,3}.
[src:diameter/5-cell] It is a 5-vertex four-dimensional object bounded by five tetrahedral cells.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The 5-cell is a 4-dimensional pyramid with a tetrahedral base and four tetrahedral sides.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The **regular 5-cell** is bounded by five regular tetrahedra, and is one of the six regular convex 4-polytopes (the four-dimensional analogues of the Platonic solids).
[src:diameter/5-cell] A regular 5-cell can be constructed from a regular tetrahedron by adding a fifth vertex one edge length distant from all the vertices of the tetrahedron.
[src:diameter/5-cell] This cannot be done in 3-dimensional space.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The regular 5-cell is a solution to the problem: *Make 10 equilateral triangles, all of the same size, using 10 matchsticks, where each side of every triangle is exactly one matchstick, and none of the triangles and matchsticks intersect one another.* No solution exists in three dimensions.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The 5-cell is the 4-dimensional simplex, the simplest possible 4-polytope.
[src:diameter/5-cell] In other words, the 5-cell is a polychoron analogous to a tetrahedron in high dimension.
[src:diameter/5-cell] It is formed by any five points which are not all in the same hyperplane (as a tetrahedron is formed by any four points which are not all in the same plane, and a triangle is formed by any three points which are not all in the same line).
[src:diameter/5-cell] Any such five points constitute a 5-cell, though not usually a regular 5-cell.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The *regular* 5-cell is not found within any of the other regular convex 4-polytopes except one: the 600-vertex 120-cell is a compound of 120 regular 5-cells.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The 5-cell is self-dual, meaning its dual polytope is 5-cell itself.
[src:diameter/5-cell] Its maximal intersection with 3-dimensional space is the triangular prism.
[src:diameter/5-cell] Its dichoral angle between cells is arccos ⁠1/4⁠ ≈ 75.52°.
[src:diameter/5-cell] Its dihedral angle between faces is arccos ⁠1/3⁠ ≈ 70.53°.
[src:diameter/5-cell] It is the first in the sequence of 6 convex regular 4-polytopes, in order of volume at a given radius or number of vertexes.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The convex hull of two 5-cells in dual configuration is the disphenoidal 30-cell, dual of the bitruncated 5-cell.
[src:diameter/5-cell] This configuration matrix represents the 5-cell.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The rows and columns correspond to vertices, edges, faces, and cells.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The diagonal numbers say how many of each element occur in the whole 5-cell.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The nondiagonal numbers say how many of the column's element occur in or at the row's element.
[src:diameter/5-cell] This self-dual polytope's matrix is identical to its 180 degree rotation.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The *k*-faces can be read as rows left of the diagonal, while the *k*-figures are read as rows after the diagonal.
[src:diameter/5-cell] All these elements of the 5-cell are enumerated in Branko Grünbaum's Venn diagram of 5 points, which is literally an illustration of the regular 5-cell in projection to the plane.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The 5-cell has only digon central planes through vertices.
[src:diameter/5-cell] It has 10 digon central planes, where each vertex pair is an edge, not an axis, of the 5-cell.
[src:diameter/5-cell] Each digon plane is orthogonal to 3 others, but completely orthogonal to none of them.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The characteristic isoclinic rotation of the 5-cell has, as pairs of invariant planes, those 10 digon planes and their completely orthogonal central planes, which are 0-gon planes which intersect no vertices of the 5-cell.
[src:diameter/5-cell] Below, a spinning 5-cell is visualized with the fourth dimension squashed and displayed as colour.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The Clifford torus is depicted in its rectangular (wrapping) form.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The A4 Coxeter plane projects the 5-cell into a regular pentagon and pentagram.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The A3 Coxeter plane projection of the 5-cell is that of a square pyramid.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The A2 Coxeter plane projection of the regular 5-cell is that of a triangular bipyramid (two tetrahedra joined face-to-face) with the two opposite vertices centered.
[src:diameter/5-cell] In the case of simplexes such as the 5-cell, certain irregular forms are in some sense more fundamental than the regular form.
[src:diameter/5-cell] Although regular 5-cells cannot fill 4-space or the regular 4-polytopes, there are irregular 5-cells which do.
[src:diameter/5-cell] These **characteristic 5-cells** are the fundamental domains of the different symmetry groups which give rise to the various 4-polytopes.
[src:diameter/5-cell] A **4-orthoscheme** is a 5-cell where all 10 faces are right triangles.
[src:diameter/5-cell] (The 5 vertices form 5 tetrahedral cells face-bonded to each other, with a total of 10 edges and 10 triangular faces.) An orthoscheme is an irregular simplex that is the convex hull of a tree in which all edges are mutually perpendicular.
[src:diameter/5-cell] In a 4-dimensional orthoscheme, the tree consists of four perpendicular edges connecting all five vertices in a linear path that makes three right-angled turns.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The elements of an orthoscheme are also orthoschemes (just as the elements of a regular simplex are also regular simplexes).
[src:diameter/5-cell] Each tetrahedral cell of a 4-orthoscheme is a 3-orthoscheme, and each triangular face is a 2-orthoscheme (a right triangle).
[src:diameter/5-cell] Orthoschemes are the characteristic simplexes of the regular polytopes, because each regular polytope is generated by reflections in the bounding facets of its particular characteristic orthoscheme.
[src:diameter/5-cell] For example, the special case of the 4-orthoscheme with equal-length perpendicular edges is the characteristic orthoscheme of the 4-cube (also called the *tesseract* or *8-cell*), the 4-dimensional analogue of the 3-dimensional cube.
[src:diameter/5-cell] If the three perpendicular edges of the 4-orthoscheme are of unit length, then all its edges are of length √1, √2, √3, or √4, precisely the chord lengths of the unit 4-cube (the lengths of the 4-cube's edges and its various diagonals).
[src:diameter/5-cell] Therefore this 4-orthoscheme fits within the 4-cube, and the 4-cube (like every regular convex polytope) can be dissected into instances of its characteristic orthoscheme.
[src:diameter/5-cell] A 3-orthoscheme is easily illustrated, but a 4-orthoscheme is more difficult to visualize.
[src:diameter/5-cell] A 4-orthoscheme is a tetrahedral pyramid with a 3-orthoscheme as its base.
[src:diameter/5-cell] It has four more edges than the 3-orthoscheme, joining the four vertices of the base to its apex (the fifth vertex of the 5-cell).
[src:diameter/5-cell] Pick out any one of the 3-orthoschemes of the six shown in the 3-cube illustration.
[src:diameter/5-cell] Notice that it touches four of the cube's eight vertices, and those four vertices are linked by a 3-edge path that makes two right-angled turns.
[src:diameter/5-cell] Imagine that this 3-orthoscheme is the base of a 4-orthoscheme, so that from each of those four vertices, an unseen 4-orthoscheme edge connects to a fifth apex vertex (which is outside the 3-cube and does not appear in the illustration at all).
[src:diameter/5-cell] Although the four additional edges all reach the same apex vertex, they will all be of different lengths.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The first of them, at one end of the 3-edge orthogonal path, extends that path with a fourth orthogonal √1 edge by making a third 90 degree turn and reaching perpendicularly into the fourth dimension to the apex.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The second of the four additional edges is a √2 diagonal of a cube face (not of the illustrated 3-cube, but of another of the tesseract's eight 3-cubes).
[src:diameter/5-cell] The third additional edge is a √3 diagonal of a 3-cube (again, not the original illustrated 3-cube).
[src:diameter/5-cell] The fourth additional edge (at the other end of the orthogonal path) is a long diameter of the tesseract itself, of length √4.
[src:diameter/5-cell] It reaches through the exact center of the tesseract to the antipodal vertex (a vertex of the opposing 3-cube), which is the apex.
[src:diameter/5-cell] Thus the **characteristic 5-cell of the 4-cube** has four √1 edges, three √2 edges, two √3 edges, and one √4 edge.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The 4-cube can be dissected into 24 such 4-orthoschemes eight different ways, with six 4-orthoschemes surrounding each of four orthogonal √4 tesseract long diameters.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The 4-cube can also be dissected into 384 *smaller* instances of this same characteristic 4-orthoscheme, just one way, by all of its symmetry hyperplanes at once, which divide it into 384 4-orthoschemes that all meet at the center of the 4-cube.
[src:diameter/5-cell] More generally, any regular polytope can be dissected into *g* instances of its characteristic orthoscheme that all meet at the regular polytope's center.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The number *g* is the *order* of the polytope, the number of reflected instances of its characteristic orthoscheme that comprise the polytope when a *single* mirror-surfaced orthoscheme instance is reflected in its own facets.
[src:diameter/5-cell] More generally still, characteristic simplexes are able to fill uniform polytopes because they possess all the requisite elements of the polytope.
[src:diameter/5-cell] They also possess all the requisite angles between elements (from 90 degrees on down).
[src:diameter/5-cell] The characteristic simplexes are the genetic codes of polytopes: like a Swiss Army knife, they contain one of everything needed to construct the polytope by replication.
[src:diameter/5-cell] Every regular polytope, including the regular 5-cell, has its characteristic orthoscheme.
[src:diameter/5-cell] There is a 4-orthoscheme which is the **characteristic 5-cell of the regular 5-cell**.
[src:diameter/5-cell] It is a tetrahedral pyramid based on the characteristic tetrahedron of the regular tetrahedron.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The regular 5-cell can be dissected into 120 instances of this characteristic 4-orthoscheme just one way, by all of its symmetry hyperplanes at once, which divide it into 120 4-orthoschemes that all meet at the center of the regular 5-cell.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The characteristic 5-cell (4-orthoscheme) of the regular 5-cell has four more edges than its base characteristic tetrahedron (3-orthoscheme), which join the four vertices of the base to its apex (the fifth vertex of the 4-orthoscheme, at the center of the regular 5-cell).
[src:diameter/5-cell] The four edges of each 4-orthoscheme which meet at the center of a regular 4-polytope are of unequal length, because they are the four characteristic radii of the regular 4-polytope: a vertex radius, an edge center radius, a face center radius, and a cell center radius.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The **tetrahedral pyramid** is a special case of a **5-cell**, a polyhedral pyramid, constructed as a regular tetrahedron base in a 3-space hyperplane, and an apex point *above* the hyperplane.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The four *sides* of the pyramid are made of triangular pyramid cells.
[src:diameter/5-cell] Many uniform 5-polytopes have **tetrahedral pyramid** vertex figures with Schläfli symbols ( )∨{3,3}.
[src:diameter/5-cell] Other uniform 5-polytopes have irregular 5-cell vertex figures.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The symmetry of a vertex figure of a uniform polytope is represented by removing the ringed nodes of the Coxeter diagram.
[src:diameter/5-cell] A 5-cell can be constructed as a Boerdijk–Coxeter helix of five chained tetrahedra, folded into a 4-dimensional ring.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The 10 triangle faces can be seen in a 2D net within a triangular tiling, with 6 triangles around every vertex, although folding into 4-dimensions causes edges to coincide.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The purple edges form a regular pentagon which is the Petrie polygon of the 5-cell.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The blue edges connect every second vertex, forming a pentagram which is the *Clifford polygon* of the 5-cell.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The pentagram's blue edges are chords of the 5-cell's *isocline*, the circular rotational path its vertices take during an isoclinic rotation, also known as a Clifford displacement.
[src:diameter/5-cell] When a net of five tetrahedra is folded up in 4-dimensional space such that each tetrahedron is face bonded to the other four, the resulting 5-cell has a total of 5 vertices, 10 edges, and 10 faces.
[src:diameter/5-cell] Four edges meet at each vertex, and three tetrahedral cells meet at each edge.
[src:diameter/5-cell] This makes the six tetrahedron as its cell.
[src:diameter/5-cell] Scaling these or the previous set of coordinates by ${\tfrac {\sqrt {5}}{4}}$ give ***unit-radius*** origin-centered regular 5-cells with edge lengths ${\sqrt {\tfrac {5}{2}}}$ .
[src:diameter/5-cell] The vertices of a 4-simplex (with edge √2 and radius 1) can be more simply constructed on a hyperplane in 5-space, as (distinct) permutations of (0,0,0,0,1) *or* (0,1,1,1,1); in these positions it is a facet of, respectively, the 5-orthoplex or the rectified penteract.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The compound of two 5-cells in dual configurations can be seen in this A5 Coxeter plane projection, with a red and blue 5-cell vertices and edges.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The intersection of these two 5-cells is a uniform bitruncated 5-cell. = ∩ .
[src:diameter/5-cell] This compound can be seen as the 4D analogue of the 2D hexagram {⁠6/2⁠} and the 3D compound of two tetrahedra.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The pentachoron (5-cell) is the simplest of 9 uniform polychora constructed from the [3,3,3] Coxeter group.
[src:diameter/5-cell] It is in the {p,3,3} sequence of regular polychora with a tetrahedral vertex figure: the tesseract {4,3,3} and 120-cell {5,3,3} of Euclidean 4-space, and the hexagonal tiling honeycomb {6,3,3} of hyperbolic space.
[src:diameter/5-cell] It is one of three {3,3,p} regular 4-polytopes with tetrahedral cells, along with the 16-cell {3,3,4} and 600-cell {3,3,5}.
[src:diameter/5-cell] The order-6 tetrahedral honeycomb {3,3,6} of hyperbolic space also has tetrahedral cells.
[src:diameter/5-cell] It is self-dual like the 24-cell {3,4,3}, having a palindromic {3,p,3} Schläfli symbol.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] In mathematics, **affine geometry** is what remains of Euclidean geometry when ignoring (mathematicians often say "forgetting") the metric notions of distance and angle.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] As the notion of *parallel lines* is one of the main properties that is independent of any metric, affine geometry is often considered as the study of parallel lines.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Therefore, Playfair's axiom (Given a line L and a point P not on L, there is exactly one line parallel to L that passes through P.) is fundamental in affine geometry.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Comparisons of figures in affine geometry are made with affine transformations, which are mappings that preserve alignment of points and parallelism of lines.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Affine geometry can be developed in two ways that are essentially equivalent.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] In synthetic geometry, an affine space is a set of *points* to which is associated a set of lines, which satisfy some axioms (such as Playfair's axiom).
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Affine geometry can also be developed on the basis of linear algebra.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] By choosing any point as "origin", the points are in one-to-one correspondence with the vectors, but there is no preferred choice for the origin; thus an affine space may be viewed as obtained from its associated vector space by "forgetting" the origin (zero vector).
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] The idea of forgetting the metric can be applied in the theory of manifolds.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] That is developed in the article *Affine connection*.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] In 1748, Leonhard Euler introduced the term *affine* (from Latin *affinis* 'related') in his book *Introductio in analysin infinitorum* (volume 2, chapter XVIII).
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] In 1827, August Möbius wrote on affine geometry in his *Der barycentrische Calcul* (chapter 3).
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] After Felix Klein's Erlangen program, affine geometry was recognized as a generalization of Euclidean geometry.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] In 1918, Hermann Weyl referred to affine geometry for his text *Space, Time, Matter*.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] He used affine geometry to introduce vector addition and subtraction at the earliest stages of his development of mathematical physics.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] of light-signals in four-dimensional space-time.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] ; then the parallel transport in question is such that it carries any null-vector at one point into the position of a null-vector at a neighboring point.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] The various types of affine geometry correspond to what interpretation is taken for *rotation*.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Euclidean geometry corresponds to the ordinary idea of rotation, while Minkowski's geometry corresponds to hyperbolic rotation.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] With respect to perpendicular lines, they remain perpendicular when the plane is subjected to ordinary rotation.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] In the Minkowski geometry, lines that are hyperbolic-orthogonal remain in that relation when the plane is subjected to hyperbolic rotation.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] (Desargues) Given seven distinct points A, A', B, B', C, C', O, such that AA', BB', CC' are distinct lines through O, and AB is parallel to A'B', and BC is parallel to B'C', then AC is parallel to A'C'.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] The affine concept of parallelism forms an equivalence relation on lines.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Since the axioms of ordered geometry as presented here include properties that imply the structure of the real numbers, those properties carry over here so that this is an axiomatization of affine geometry over the field of real numbers.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] The first non-Desarguesian plane was noted by David Hilbert in his *Foundations of Geometry*.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] The Moulton plane is a standard illustration.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] In order to provide a context for such geometry as well as those where Desargues theorem is valid, the concept of a ternary ring was developed by Marshall Hall.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] In this approach affine planes are constructed from ordered pairs taken from a ternary ring.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] A plane is said to have the "minor affine Desargues property" when two triangles in parallel perspective, having two parallel sides, must also have the third sides parallel.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] If this property holds in the affine plane defined by a ternary ring, then there is an equivalence relation between "vectors" defined by pairs of points from the plane.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Geometrically, affine transformations (affinities) preserve collinearity: so they transform parallel lines into parallel lines and preserve ratios of distances along parallel lines.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] We identify as *affine theorems* any geometric result that is invariant under the affine group (in Felix Klein's Erlangen programme this is its underlying group of symmetry transformations for affine geometry).
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Consider in a vector space V, the general linear group GL(*V*).
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] It is not the whole *affine group* because we must allow also translations by vectors v in V.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] For example, the theorem from the plane geometry of triangles about the concurrence of the lines joining each vertex to the midpoint of the opposite side (at the *centroid* or *barycenter*) depends on the notions of *mid-point* and *centroid* as affine invariants.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Other examples include the theorems of Ceva and Menelaus.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Affine invariants can also assist calculations.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] For example, the lines that divide the area of a triangle into two equal halves form an envelope inside the triangle.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] The ratio of the area of the envelope to the area of the triangle is affine invariant, and so only needs to be calculated from a simple case such as a unit isosceles right angled triangle to give ${\tfrac {3}{4}}\log _{e}(2)-{\tfrac {1}{2}},$ i.e.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Familiar formulas such as half the base times the height for the area of a triangle, or a third the base times the height for the volume of a pyramid, are likewise affine invariants.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] While the latter is less obvious than the former for the general case, it is easily seen for the one-sixth of the unit cube formed by a face (area 1) and the midpoint of the cube (height 1/2).
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Hence it holds for all pyramids, even slanting ones whose apex is not directly above the center of the base, and those with base a parallelogram instead of a square.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] The formula further generalizes to pyramids whose base can be dissected into parallelograms, including cones by allowing infinitely many parallelograms (with due attention to convergence).
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] The same approach shows that a four-dimensional pyramid has 4D hypervolume one quarter the 3D volume of its parallelepiped base times the height, and so on for higher dimensions.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Two types of affine transformation are used in kinematics, both classical and modern.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Velocity *v* is described using length and direction, where length is presumed unbounded.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] This variety of kinematics, styled as Galilean or Newtonian, uses coordinates of absolute space and time.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] The shear mapping of a plane with an axis for each represents coordinate change for an observer moving with velocity *v* in a resting frame of reference.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Finite light speed, first noted by the delay in appearance of the moons of Jupiter, requires a modern kinematics.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] The method involves rapidity instead of velocity, and substitutes squeeze mapping for the shear mapping used earlier.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] This affine geometry was developed synthetically in 1912. to express the special theory of relativity.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] In 1984, "the affine plane associated to the Lorentzian vector space *L*2" was described by Graciela Birman and Katsumi Nomizu in an article entitled "Trigonometry in Lorentzian geometry".
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Affine geometry can be viewed as the geometry of an affine space of a given dimension *n*, coordinatized over a field *K*.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] There is also (in two dimensions) a combinatorial generalization of coordinatized affine space, as developed in synthetic finite geometry.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] In projective geometry, *affine space* means the complement of a hyperplane at infinity in a projective space.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] *Affine space* can also be viewed as a vector space whose operations are limited to those linear combinations whose coefficients sum to one, for example 2*x* − *y*, *x* − *y* + *z*, (*x* + *y* + *z*)/3, **i***x* + (1 − **i**)*y*, etc.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Synthetically, affine planes are 2-dimensional affine geometries defined in terms of the relations between points and lines (or sometimes, in higher dimensions, hyperplanes).
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Defining affine (and projective) geometries as configurations of points and lines (or hyperplanes) instead of using coordinates, one gets examples with no coordinate fields.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] A major property is that all such examples have dimension 2.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Finite examples in dimension 2 (finite affine planes) have been valuable in the study of configurations in infinite affine spaces, in group theory, and in combinatorics.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Despite being less general than the configurational approach, the other approaches discussed have been very successful in illuminating the parts of geometry that are related to symmetry.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] In traditional geometry, affine geometry is considered to be a study between Euclidean geometry and projective geometry.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] On the one hand, affine geometry is Euclidean geometry with congruence left out; on the other hand, affine geometry may be obtained from projective geometry by the designation of a particular line or plane to represent the points at infinity.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] In affine geometry, there is no metric structure but the parallel postulate does hold.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] Affine geometry provides the basis for Euclidean structure when perpendicular lines are defined, or the basis for Minkowski geometry through the notion of hyperbolic orthogonality.
[src:diameter/affine-geometry] In this viewpoint, an affine transformation is a projective transformation that does not permute finite points with points at infinity, and affine transformation geometry is the study of geometrical properties through the action of the group of affine transformations.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The fundamental objects of study in algebraic geometry are algebraic varieties, which are geometric manifestations of solutions of systems of polynomial equations.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Examples of the most studied classes of algebraic varieties are lines, circles, parabolas, ellipses, hyperbolas, cubic curves like elliptic curves, and quartic curves like lemniscates and Cassini ovals.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] A point of the plane lies on an algebraic curve if its coordinates satisfy a given polynomial equation.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Basic questions involve the study of points of special interest like singular points, inflection points and points at infinity.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] More advanced questions involve the topology of the curve and the relationship between curves defined by different equations.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Algebraic geometry occupies a central place in modern mathematics and has multiple conceptual connections with such diverse fields as complex analysis, topology and number theory.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] As a study of systems of polynomial equations in several variables, the subject of algebraic geometry begins with finding specific solutions via equation solving, and then proceeds to understand the intrinsic properties of the totality of solutions of a system of equations.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] This understanding requires both conceptual theory and computational technique.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] In the 20th century, algebraic geometry split into several subareas.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] One key achievement of this abstract algebraic geometry is Grothendieck's scheme theory which allows one to use sheaf theory to study algebraic varieties in a way which is very similar to its use in the study of differential and analytic manifolds.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] This is obtained by extending the notion of point: In classical algebraic geometry, a point of an affine variety may be identified, through Hilbert's Nullstellensatz, with a maximal ideal of the coordinate ring, while the points of the corresponding affine scheme are all prime ideals of this ring.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] This means that a point of such a scheme may be either a usual point or a sub-variety.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] This approach also enables a unification of the language and the tools of classical algebraic geometry, mainly concerned with complex points, and of algebraic number theory.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Wiles' proof of the longstanding conjecture called Fermat's Last Theorem is an example of the power of this approach.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] In classical algebraic geometry, the main objects of interest are the vanishing sets of collections of polynomials, meaning the set of all points that simultaneously satisfy one or more polynomial equations.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] In classical algebraic geometry, this field was always the complex numbers **C**, but many of the same results are true if we assume only that *k* is algebraically closed.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] We consider the affine space of dimension *n* over *k*, denoted **A**n(*k*) (or more simply **A***n*, when *k* is clear from the context).
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] When one fixes a coordinate system, one may identify **A**n(*k*) with *k**n*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The purpose of not working with *k**n* is to emphasize that one "forgets" the vector space structure that *k*n carries.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The property of a function to be polynomial (or regular) does not depend on the choice of a coordinate system in **A***n*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] When a coordinate system is chosen, the regular functions on the affine *n*-space may be identified with the ring of polynomial functions in *n* variables over *k*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Therefore, the set of the regular functions on **A***n* is a ring, which is denoted *k*[**A***n*].
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] We say that a polynomial *vanishes* at a point if evaluating it at that point gives zero.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Let *S* be a set of polynomials in *k*[**A**n].
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The *vanishing set of S* (or *vanishing locus* or *zero set*) is the set *V*(*S*) of all points in **A***n* where every polynomial in *S* vanishes.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] A subset of **A***n* which is *V*(*S*), for some *S*, is called an *algebraic set*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The *V* stands for *variety* (a specific type of algebraic set to be defined below).
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Given a subset *U* of **A***n*, can one recover the set of polynomials which generate it?
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] If *U* is *any* subset of **A***n*, define *I*(*U*) to be the set of all polynomials whose vanishing set contains *U*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The *I* stands for ideal: if two polynomials *f* and *g* both vanish on *U*, then *f*+*g* vanishes on *U*, and if *h* is any polynomial, then *hf* vanishes on *U*, so *I*(*U*) is always an ideal of the polynomial ring *k*[**A***n*].
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The answer to the first question is provided by introducing the Zariski topology, a topology on **A***n* whose closed sets are the algebraic sets, and which directly reflects the algebraic structure of *k*[**A***n*].
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Then *U* = *V*(*I*(*U*)) if and only if *U* is an algebraic set or equivalently a Zariski-closed set.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The answer to the second question is given by Hilbert's Nullstellensatz.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] In one of its forms, it says that *I*(*V*(*S*)) is the radical of the ideal generated by *S*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] In more abstract language, there is a Galois connection, giving rise to two closure operators; they can be identified, and naturally play a basic role in the theory; the example is elaborated at Galois connection.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] For various reasons we may not always want to work with the entire ideal corresponding to an algebraic set *U*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Hilbert's basis theorem implies that ideals in *k*[**A***n*] are always finitely generated.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] An algebraic set is called *irreducible* if it cannot be written as the union of two smaller algebraic sets.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Any algebraic set is a finite union of irreducible algebraic sets and this decomposition is unique.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Thus its elements are called the *irreducible components* of the algebraic set.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] An irreducible algebraic set is also called a *variety*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] It turns out that an algebraic set is a variety if and only if it may be defined as the vanishing set of a prime ideal of the polynomial ring.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Some authors do not make a clear distinction between algebraic sets and varieties and use *irreducible variety* to make the distinction when needed.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Just as continuous functions are the natural maps on topological spaces and smooth functions are the natural maps on differentiable manifolds, there is a natural class of functions on an algebraic set, called *regular functions* or *polynomial functions*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] A regular function on an algebraic set *V* contained in **A***n* is the restriction to *V* of a regular function on **A***n*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] For an algebraic set defined on the field of the complex numbers, the regular functions are smooth and even analytic.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Just as with the regular functions on affine space, the regular functions on *V* form a ring, which we denote by *k*[*V*].
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] This ring is called the *coordinate ring of V*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Since regular functions on V come from regular functions on **A***n*, there is a relationship between the coordinate rings.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Specifically, if a regular function on *V* is the restriction of two functions *f* and *g* in *k*[**A***n*], then *f* − *g* is a polynomial function which is null on *V* and thus belongs to *I*(*V*).
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Using regular functions from an affine variety to **A**1, we can define regular maps from one affine variety to another.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] First we will define a regular map from a variety into affine space: Let *V* be a variety contained in **A***n*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Choose *m* regular functions on *V*, and call them *f*1, . . ., *f**m*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] In other words, each *f**i* determines one coordinate of the range of *f*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] If *V*′ is a variety contained in **A***m*, we say that *f* is a *regular map* from *V* to *V*′ if the range of *f* is contained in *V*′.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The definition of the regular maps apply also to algebraic sets.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The regular maps are also called *morphisms*, as they make the collection of all affine algebraic sets into a category, where the objects are the affine algebraic sets and the morphisms are the regular maps.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The affine varieties is a subcategory of the category of the algebraic sets.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Given a regular map *g* from *V* to *V*′ and a regular function *f* of *k*[*V*′], then *f* ∘ *g* ∈ *k*[*V*].
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Conversely, every ring homomorphism from *k*[*V*′] to *k*[*V*] defines a regular map from *V* to *V*′.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] This defines an equivalence of categories between the category of algebraic sets and the opposite category of the finitely generated reduced *k*-algebras.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] This equivalence is one of the starting points of scheme theory.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] In contrast to the preceding sections, this section concerns only varieties and not algebraic sets.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] On the other hand, the definitions extend naturally to projective varieties (next section), as an affine variety and its projective completion have the same field of functions.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] If *V* is an affine variety, its coordinate ring is an integral domain and has thus a field of fractions which is denoted *k*(*V*) and called the *field of the rational functions* on *V* or, shortly, the *function field* of *V*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Its elements are the restrictions to *V* of the rational functions over the affine space containing *V*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The domain of a rational function *f* is not *V* but the complement of the sub-variety (a hypersurface) where the denominator of *f* vanishes.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] As with regular maps, one may define a *rational map* from a variety *V* to a variety *V*'.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] As with the regular maps, the rational maps from *V* to *V*' may be identified to the field homomorphisms from *k*(*V*') to *k*(*V*).
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Two affine varieties are *birationally equivalent* if there are two rational functions between them which are inverse one to the other in the regions where both are defined.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Equivalently, they are birationally equivalent if their function fields are isomorphic.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] An affine variety is a *rational variety* if it is birationally equivalent to an affine space.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] This means that the variety admits a *rational parameterization*, that is a parametrization with rational functions.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] which may also be viewed as a rational map from the line to the circle.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The problem of resolution of singularities is to know if every algebraic variety is birationally equivalent to a variety whose projective completion is non-singular (see also smooth completion).
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] It was solved in the affirmative in characteristic 0 by Heisuke Hironaka in 1964 and is yet unsolved in finite characteristic.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Whereas the complex numbers are obtained by adding the number *i*, a root of the polynomial *x*2 + 1, projective space is obtained by adding in appropriate points "at infinity", points where parallel lines may meet.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] To see how this might come about, consider the variety *V*(*y* − *x*2).
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] As *x* goes to positive infinity, the slope of the line from the origin to the point (*x*, *x*2) also goes to positive infinity.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] As *x* goes to negative infinity, the slope of the same line goes to negative infinity.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Compare this to the variety *V*(*y* − *x*3).
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] As *x* goes to positive infinity, the slope of the line from the origin to the point (*x*, *x*3) goes to positive infinity just as before.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] But unlike before, as *x* goes to negative infinity, the slope of the same line goes to positive infinity as well; the exact opposite of the parabola.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] So the behaviour "at infinity" of *V*(*y* − *x*3) is different from the behaviour "at infinity" of *V*(*y* − *x*2).
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Also, both curves are rational, as they are parameterized by *x*, and the Riemann-Roch theorem implies that the cubic curve must have a singularity, which must be at infinity, as all its points in the affine space are regular.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Thus many of the properties of algebraic varieties, including birational equivalence and all the topological properties, depend on the behavior "at infinity" and so it is natural to study the varieties in projective space.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Furthermore, the introduction of projective techniques made many theorems in algebraic geometry simpler and sharper: For example, Bézout's theorem on the number of intersection points between two varieties can be stated in its sharpest form only in projective space.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] For these reasons, projective space plays a fundamental role in algebraic geometry.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Nowadays, the *projective space* **P***n* of dimension *n* is usually defined as the set of the lines passing through a point, considered as the origin, in the affine space of dimension *n* + 1, or equivalently to the set of the vector lines in a vector space of dimension *n* + 1.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] When a coordinate system has been chosen in the space of dimension *n* + 1, all the points of a line have the same set of coordinates, up to the multiplication by an element of *k*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] This defines the homogeneous coordinates of a point of **P***n* as a sequence of *n* + 1 elements of the base field *k*, defined up to the multiplication by a nonzero element of *k* (the same for the whole sequence).
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] A polynomial in *n* + 1 variables vanishes at all points of a line passing through the origin if and only if it is homogeneous.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] In this case, one says that the polynomial *vanishes* at the corresponding point of **P***n*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] This allows us to define a *projective algebraic set* in **P***n* as the set *V*(*f*1, ..., *f**k*), where a finite set of homogeneous polynomials {*f*1, ..., *f**k*} vanishes.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Like for affine algebraic sets, there is a bijection between the projective algebraic sets and the reduced homogeneous ideals which define them.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The *projective varieties* are the projective algebraic sets whose defining ideal is prime.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Every projective algebraic set may be uniquely decomposed into a finite union of projective varieties.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The only regular functions which may be defined properly on a projective variety are the constant functions.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Thus this notion is not used in projective situations.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] On the other hand, the *field of the rational functions* or *function field* is a useful notion, which, similarly to the affine case, is defined as the set of the quotients of two homogeneous elements of the same degree in the homogeneous coordinate ring.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Real algebraic geometry is the study of real algebraic varieties.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The fact that the field of the real numbers is an ordered field cannot be ignored in such a study.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] For example, the curve of equation $x^{2}+y^{2}-a=0$ is a circle if $a>0$ , but has no real points if $a<0$ .
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Real algebraic geometry also investigates, more broadly, *semi-algebraic sets*, which are the solutions of systems of polynomial inequalities.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] For example, neither branch of the hyperbola of equation $xy-1=0$ is a real algebraic variety.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] However, the branch in the first quadrant is a semi-algebraic set defined by $xy-1=0$ and $x>0$ .
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] One open problem in real algebraic geometry is the following part of Hilbert's sixteenth problem: Decide which respective positions are possible for the ovals of a non-singular plane curve of degree 8.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] One may date the origin of computational algebraic geometry to meeting EUROSAM'79 (International Symposium on Symbolic and Algebraic Manipulation) held at Marseille, France, in June 1979.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Since then, most results in this area are related to one or several of these items either by using or improving one of these algorithms, or by finding algorithms whose complexity is singly exponential in the number of the variables.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] A body of mathematical theory complementary to symbolic methods called numerical algebraic geometry has been developed over the last several decades.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The main computational method is homotopy continuation.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] This supports, for example, a model of floating-point computation for solving problems of algebraic geometry.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] A Gröbner basis is a system of generators of a polynomial ideal whose computation allows the deduction of many properties of the affine algebraic variety defined by the ideal.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Gröbner basis computations do not allow one to compute directly the primary decomposition of *I* nor the prime ideals defining the irreducible components of *V*, but most algorithms for this involve Gröbner basis computation.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The algorithms which are not based on Gröbner bases use regular chains but may need Gröbner bases in some exceptional situations.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Gröbner bases are deemed to be difficult to compute.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] In fact they may contain, in the worst case, polynomials whose degree is doubly exponential in the number of variables and a number of polynomials which is also doubly exponential.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] However, this is only a worst-case complexity, and the complexity bound of Lazard's algorithm of 1979 may frequently apply.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Faugère F5 algorithm realizes this complexity, as it may be viewed as an improvement of Lazard's 1979 algorithm.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] It follows that the best implementations allow one to compute almost routinely with algebraic sets of degree more than 100.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] This means that, presently, the difficulty of computing a Gröbner basis is strongly related to the intrinsic difficulty of the problem.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] CAD is an algorithm which was introduced in 1973 by G.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Collins to implement with an acceptable complexity the Tarski–Seidenberg theorem on quantifier elimination over the real numbers.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] This theorem concerns the formulas of the first-order logic whose atomic formulas are polynomial equalities or inequalities between polynomials with real coefficients.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] These formulas are thus the formulas which may be constructed from the atomic formulas by the logical operators *and* (∧), *or* (∨), *not* (¬), *for all* (∀), and *there exists* (∃).
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Tarski's theorem asserts that, from such a formula, one may compute an equivalent formula without quantifiers (∀, ∃).
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The complexity of CAD is doubly exponential in the number of variables.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] This means that CAD allows one, in theory, to solve every problem of real algebraic geometry which may be expressed by such a formula—this is almost every problem concerning explicitly given varieties and semi-algebraic sets.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] While Gröbner basis computation has doubly exponential complexity only in rare cases, CAD has almost always this high complexity.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] This implies that, unless most polynomials appearing in the input are linear, it may not solve problems with more than four variables.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Since 1973, most of the research on this subject is devoted either to improving CAD or finding alternative algorithms in special cases of general interest.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] As an example of the state of art, there are efficient algorithms to find at least one point in every connected component of a semi-algebraic set, and thus to test whether a semi-algebraic set is empty.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] On the other hand, CAD is yet, in practice, the best algorithm to count the number of connected components.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The basic general algorithms of computational geometry have a doubly exponential worst-case complexity.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] More precisely, if *d* is the maximal degree of the input polynomials and *n* the number of variables, then their complexity is at most *d*2*cn* for some constant *c*, and, for some inputs, the complexity is at least *d*2*c′n* for another constant *c*′.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] During the last 20 years of the 20th century, various algorithms were introduced to solve specific subproblems with a better complexity.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Most of these algorithms have a complexity $d^{O(n^{2})}$ .
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The main algorithms of real algebraic geometry which solve a problem solved by CAD are related to the topology of semi-algebraic sets.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] One may cite *counting the number of connected components*, *testing whether two points are in the same components*, and *computing a Whitney stratification of a real algebraic set*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] They have a complexity of $d^{O(n^{2})}$ , but the constant involved by *O* notation is so high that using them to solve any nontrivial problem effectively solved by CAD, is impossible even if one could use all the existing computing power in the world.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Therefore, these algorithms have never been implemented and it is an active research area to search for algorithms with have together a good asymptotic complexity and a good practical efficiency.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The modern approaches to algebraic geometry redefine and effectively extend the range of basic objects in various levels of generality to schemes, formal schemes, ind-schemes, algebraic spaces, algebraic stacks, and so on.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Most remarkably, in the early 1960s, algebraic varieties were subsumed into Alexander Grothendieck's concept of a scheme.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The gluing is along the Zariski topology; one can glue within the category of locally ringed spaces, but also, using the Yoneda embedding, within the more abstract category of presheaves of sets over the category of affine schemes.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The Zariski topology in the set-theoretic sense is then replaced by a Grothendieck topology.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Sheaves can be furthermore generalized to stacks in the sense of Grothendieck, usually with some additional representability conditions leading to Artin stacks and, even finer, Deligne–Mumford stacks, both often called algebraic stacks.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Sometimes, other algebraic sites replace the category of affine schemes.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] For example, Nikolai Durov has introduced commutative algebraic monads as a generalization of local objects in a generalized algebraic geometry.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Versions of a tropical geometry, of an absolute geometry over a field of one element, and an algebraic analogue of Arakelov's geometry were realized in this setup.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Another formal generalization is possible to universal algebraic geometry in which every variety of algebras has its own algebraic geometry.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The term *variety of algebras* should not be confused with *algebraic variety*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The language of schemes, stacks, and generalizations has proved to be a valuable way of dealing with geometric concepts and become cornerstones of modern algebraic geometry.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Algebraic stacks can be further generalized, and for many practical questions like deformation theory and intersection theory, this is often the most natural approach.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] One can also replace presheaves of sets with presheaves of simplicial sets (or of infinity groupoids).
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Another (noncommutative) version of derived algebraic geometry, using A-infinity categories, has been developed from the early 1990s by Maxim Kontsevich and followers.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Some of the roots of algebraic geometry date back to the work of the Hellenistic Greeks from the 5th century BC.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The Delian problem, for instance, was to construct a length *x* so that the cube of side *x* contained the same volume as the rectangular box *a*2*b* for given sides *a* and *b*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] 350 BC) considered the problem geometrically by intersecting the pair of plane conics *ay* = *x*2 and *xy* = *ab*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] In the 3rd century BC, Archimedes and Apollonius systematically studied additional problems on conic sections using coordinates.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Apollonius in the Conics further developed a method that is so similar to analytic geometry that his work is sometimes thought to have anticipated the work of Descartes by some 1800 years.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] He further developed relations between the abscissas and the corresponding coordinates using geometric methods like using parabolas and curves.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Medieval mathematicians, including Omar Khayyam, Leonardo of Pisa, Gersonides and Nicole Oresme in the Medieval Period, solved certain cubic and quadratic equations by purely algebraic means and then interpreted the results geometrically.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The Persian mathematician Omar Khayyám (born 1048 AD) believed that there was a relationship between arithmetic, algebra, and geometry.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] This was criticized by Jeffrey Oaks, who claims that the study of curves by means of equations originated with Descartes in the seventeenth century.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Such techniques of applying geometrical constructions to algebraic problems were also adopted by a number of Renaissance mathematicians such as Gerolamo Cardano and Niccolò Fontana "Tartaglia" on their studies of the cubic equation.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The geometrical approach to construction problems, rather than the algebraic one, was favored by most 16th- and 17th-century mathematicians, notably Blaise Pascal who argued against the use of algebraic and analytical methods in geometry.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The French mathematicians Franciscus Vieta and later René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat revolutionized the conventional way of thinking about construction problems through the introduction of coordinate geometry.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] They were interested primarily in the properties of *algebraic curves*, such as those defined by Diophantine equations (in the case of Fermat), and the algebraic reformulation of the classical Greek works on conics and cubics (in the case of Descartes).
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] During the same period, Blaise Pascal and Gérard Desargues approached geometry from a different perspective, developing the synthetic notions of projective geometry.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Pascal and Desargues also studied curves, but from the purely geometrical point of view: the analog of the Greek *ruler-and-compass construction*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Ultimately, the analytic geometry of Descartes and Fermat won out, for it supplied the 18th-century mathematicians with concrete quantitative tools needed to study physical problems using the new calculus of Newton and Leibniz.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] However, by the end of the 18th century, most of the algebraic character of coordinate geometry was subsumed by the *calculus of infinitesimals* of Lagrange and Euler.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] It took the simultaneous 19th-century developments of non-Euclidean geometry and Abelian integrals in order to bring the old algebraic ideas back into the geometrical fold.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The first of these new developments was seized up by Edmond Laguerre and Arthur Cayley, who attempted to ascertain the generalized metric properties of projective space.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Cayley introduced the idea of *homogeneous polynomial forms*, and more specifically quadratic forms, on projective space.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Subsequently, Felix Klein studied projective geometry (along with other types of geometry) from the viewpoint that the geometry on a space is encoded in a certain class of transformations on the space.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] By the end of the 19th century, projective geometers were studying more general kinds of transformations on figures in projective space.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Rather than the projective linear transformations which were normally regarded as giving the fundamental Kleinian geometry on projective space, they concerned themselves also with the higher-degree birational transformations.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] This weaker notion of congruence would later lead members of the 20th century Italian school of algebraic geometry to classify algebraic surfaces up to birational isomorphism.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The second early-19th-century development, that of Abelian integrals, would lead Bernhard Riemann to the development of Riemann surfaces.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] In the same period began the algebraization of the algebraic geometry through commutative algebra.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The prominent results in this direction are Hilbert's basis theorem and Hilbert's Nullstellensatz, which are the basis of the connection between algebraic geometry and commutative algebra, and Macaulay's multivariate resultant, which is the basis of elimination theory.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Probably because of the size of the computation which is implied by multivariate resultants, elimination theory was forgotten during the middle of the 20th century until it was renewed by singularity theory and computational algebraic geometry.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] L. van der Waerden, Oscar Zariski, and André Weil developed a foundation for algebraic geometry based on contemporary commutative algebra, including valuation theory and the theory of ideals.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] One of the goals was to give a rigorous framework for proving the results of the Italian school of algebraic geometry.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] In particular, this school used systematically the notion of generic point without any precise definition, which was first given by these authors during the 1930s.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] In the 1950s and 1960s, Jean-Pierre Serre and Alexander Grothendieck recast the foundations making use of sheaf theory.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Later, from about 1960, and largely led by Grothendieck, the idea of schemes was worked out, in conjunction with a very refined apparatus of homological techniques.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] After a decade of rapid development the field stabilized in the 1970s, and new applications were made, both to number theory and to more classical geometric questions on algebraic varieties, singularities, moduli, and formal moduli.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] An important class of varieties, not easily understood directly from their defining equations, are the abelian varieties, which are the projective varieties whose points form an abelian group.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The prototypical examples are the elliptic curves, which have a rich theory.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] They were instrumental in the proof of Fermat's Last Theorem and are also used in elliptic-curve cryptography.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] In parallel with the abstract trend of the algebraic geometry, which is concerned with general statements about varieties, methods for effective computation with concretely-given varieties have also been developed, which lead to the new area of computational algebraic geometry.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] One of the founding methods of this area is the theory of Gröbner bases, introduced by Bruno Buchberger in 1965.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Another founding method, more specially devoted to real algebraic geometry, is the cylindrical algebraic decomposition, introduced by George E.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] An **analytic variety** over the field of real or complex numbers is defined locally as the set of common solutions of several equations involving analytic functions.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] It is analogous to the concept of algebraic variety in that it carries a structure sheaf of analytic functions instead of regular functions.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Any complex manifold is a complex analytic variety.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Since analytic varieties may have singular points, not all complex analytic varieties are manifolds.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Over a non-archimedean field analytic geometry is studied via rigid analytic spaces.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Modern analytic geometry over the field of complex numbers is closely related to complex algebraic geometry, as has been shown by Jean-Pierre Serre in his paper *GAGA*, the name of which is French for *Algebraic geometry and analytic geometry*.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] The GAGA results over the field of complex numbers may be extended to rigid analytic spaces over non-archimedean fields.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] Algebraic geometry now finds applications in statistics, control theory, robotics, error-correcting codes, phylogenetics and geometric modelling.
[src:diameter/algebraic-geometry] There are also connections to string theory, game theory, graph matchings, solitons and integer programming.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Ibn al-Haytham was the first to correctly prove vision as intromissive rather than extramissive, and to argue that vision occurs in the brain, pointing to observations that it is subjective and affected by personal experience.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He also stated a principle of least time for refraction, similar to the results of the much later results from Fermat's principle.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He made major contributions to catoptrics and dioptrics by studying reflection, refraction and nature of images formed by light rays.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He was the first physicist to give a complete statement of the law of reflection, and was also the first to describe the horopter, spherical aberration, color constancy, and unconscious inference.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He was also a polymath, writing on philosophy, theology and medicine.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Born in Basra, he spent most of his productive period in the Fatimid capital of Cairo and earned his living authoring various treatises and tutoring members of the nobilities.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Ibn al-Haytham is sometimes given the byname *al-Baṣrī* after his birthplace, or *al-Miṣrī* ('the Egyptian').
[src:diameter/alhazen] Al-Haytham was dubbed the "Second Ptolemy" by Abu'l-Hasan Bayhaqi and "The Physicist" by John Peckham.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Ibn al-Haytham paved the way for the modern science of physical optics.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Upon his return to Cairo, he was given an administrative post.
[src:diameter/alhazen] After he proved unable to fulfill this task as well, he contracted the ire of the caliph Al-Hakim, and is said to have been forced into hiding until the caliph's death in 1021, after which his confiscated possessions were returned to him.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Legend has it that Alhazen feigned madness and was kept under house arrest during this period.
[src:diameter/alhazen] During this time, he wrote his influential *Book of Optics*.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen continued to live in Cairo, in the neighborhood of the famous University of al-Azhar, and lived from the proceeds of his literary production until his death in c.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Among his students were Sorkhab (Sohrab), a Persian from Semnan, and Abu al-Wafa Mubashir ibn Fatek, an Egyptian prince.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen's most famous work is his seven-volume treatise on optics *Kitab al-Manazir* (*Book of Optics*), written from 1011 to 1021.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In it, Ibn al-Haytham was the first to explain that vision occurs when light reflects from an object and then passes to one's eyes, and to argue that vision occurs in the brain, pointing to observations that it is subjective and affected by personal experience.
[src:diameter/alhazen] This work enjoyed a great reputation during the Middle Ages.
[src:diameter/alhazen] The Latin version of *De aspectibus* was translated at the end of the 14th century into Italian vernacular, under the title *De li aspecti*.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Risner is also the author of the name variant "Alhazen"; before Risner he was known in the west as Alhacen.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Works by Alhazen on geometric subjects were discovered in the Bibliothèque nationale in Paris in 1834 by E.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Mark Smith has accounted for 18 full or near-complete manuscripts, and five fragments, which are preserved in 14 locations, including one in the Bodleian Library at Oxford, and one in the library of Bruges.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Two major theories on vision prevailed in classical antiquity.
[src:diameter/alhazen] The first theory, the emission theory, was supported by such thinkers as Euclid and Ptolemy, who believed that sight worked by the eye emitting rays of light.
[src:diameter/alhazen] The second theory, the intromission theory supported by Aristotle and his followers, had physical forms entering the eye from an object.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Previous Islamic writers (such as al-Kindi) had argued essentially on Euclidean, Galenist, or Aristotelian lines.
[src:diameter/alhazen] The strongest influence on the *Book of Optics* was from Ptolemy's *Optics*, while the description of the anatomy and physiology of the eye was based on Galen's account.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen's achievement was to come up with a theory that successfully combined parts of the mathematical ray arguments of Euclid, the medical tradition of Galen, and the intromission theories of Aristotle.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen's intromission theory followed al-Kindi (and broke with Aristotle) in asserting that "from each point of every colored body, illuminated by any light, issue light and color along every straight line that can be drawn from that point".
[src:diameter/alhazen] This left him with the problem of explaining how a coherent image was formed from many independent sources of radiation; in particular, every point of an object would send rays to every point on the eye.
[src:diameter/alhazen] What Alhazen needed was for each point on an object to correspond to one point only on the eye.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He attempted to resolve this by asserting that the eye would only perceive perpendicular rays from the object – for any one point on the eye, only the ray that reached it directly, without being refracted by any other part of the eye, would be perceived.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He later asserted (in book seven of the *Optics*) that other rays would be refracted through the eye and perceived *as if* perpendicular.
[src:diameter/alhazen] His arguments regarding perpendicular rays do not clearly explain why *only* perpendicular rays were perceived; why would the weaker oblique rays not be perceived more weakly?
[src:diameter/alhazen] His later argument that refracted rays would be perceived as if perpendicular does not seem persuasive.
[src:diameter/alhazen] However, despite its weaknesses, no other theory of the time was so comprehensive, and it was enormously influential, particularly in Western Europe.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Directly or indirectly, his *De Aspectibus* (Book of Optics) inspired much activity in optics between the 13th and 17th centuries.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Kepler's later theory of the retinal image (which resolved the problem of the correspondence of points on an object and points in the eye) built directly on the conceptual framework of Alhazen.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen showed through experiment that light travels in straight lines, and carried out various experiments with lenses, mirrors, refraction, and reflection.
[src:diameter/alhazen] His analyses of reflection and refraction considered the vertical and horizontal components of light rays separately.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen studied the process of sight, the structure of the eye, image formation in the eye, and the visual system.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Howard argued in a 1996 *Perception* article that Alhazen should be credited with many discoveries and theories previously attributed to Western Europeans writing centuries later.
[src:diameter/alhazen] For example, he described what became in the 19th century Hering's law of equal innervation.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He wrote a description of vertical horopters 600 years before Aguilonius that is actually closer to the modern definition than Aguilonius's – and his work on binocular disparity was repeated by Panum in 1858.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Craig Aaen-Stockdale, while agreeing that Alhazen should be credited with many advances, has expressed some caution, especially when considering Alhazen in isolation from Ptolemy, with whom Alhazen was extremely familiar.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen corrected a significant error of Ptolemy regarding binocular vision, but otherwise his account is very similar; Ptolemy also attempted to explain what is now called Hering's law.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In general, Alhazen built on and expanded the optics of Ptolemy.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In a more detailed account of Ibn al-Haytham's contribution to the study of binocular vision based on Lejeune and Sabra, Raynaud showed that the concepts of correspondence, homonymous and crossed diplopia were in place in Ibn al-Haytham's optics.
[src:diameter/alhazen] But contrary to Howard, he explained why Ibn al-Haytham did not give the circular figure of the horopter and why, by reasoning experimentally, he was in fact closer to the discovery of Panum's fusional area than that of the Vieth-Müller circle.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In this regard, Ibn al-Haytham's theory of binocular vision faced two main limits: the lack of recognition of the role of the retina, and obviously the lack of an experimental investigation of ocular tracts.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen's most original contribution was that, after describing how he thought the eye was anatomically constructed, he went on to consider how this anatomy would behave functionally as an optical system.
[src:diameter/alhazen] His understanding of pinhole projection from his experiments appears to have influenced his consideration of image inversion in the eye, which he sought to avoid.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He maintained that the rays that fell perpendicularly on the lens (or glacial humor as he called it) were further refracted outward as they left the glacial humor and the resulting image thus passed upright into the optic nerve at the back of the eye.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He followed Galen in believing that the lens was the receptive organ of sight, although some of his work hints that he thought the retina was also involved.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen's synthesis of light and vision adhered to the Aristotelian scheme, exhaustively describing the process of vision in a logical, complete fashion.
[src:diameter/alhazen] His research in catoptrics (the study of optical systems using mirrors) was centred on spherical and parabolic mirrors and spherical aberration.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He made the observation that the ratio between the angle of incidence and refraction does not remain constant, and investigated the magnifying power of a lens.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen was the first physicist to give complete statement of the law of reflection.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He was first to state that the incident ray, the reflected ray, and the normal to the surface all lie in a same plane perpendicular to reflecting plane.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen studied light passing through different materials and formulated laws of refraction.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He stated that light possesses a finite speed that changes depending on the material medium, and he argued that light propagates along the path that is "easier and quicker." As noted by Roshdi Rashed et al. this is an early form of Fermat's principle#History.
[src:diameter/alhazen] His work on catoptrics in Book V of the Book of Optics contains a discussion of what is now known as Alhazen's problem, first formulated by Ptolemy in 150 AD.
[src:diameter/alhazen] It comprises drawing lines from two points in the plane of a circle meeting at a point on the circumference and making equal angles with the normal at that point.
[src:diameter/alhazen] This is equivalent to finding the point on the edge of a circular billiard table at which a player must aim a cue ball at a given point to make it bounce off the table edge and hit another ball at a second given point.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Thus, its main application in optics is to solve the problem, "Given a light source and a spherical mirror, find the point on the mirror where the light will be reflected to the eye of an observer." This leads to an equation of the fourth degree.
[src:diameter/alhazen] This eventually led Alhazen to derive a formula for the sum of fourth powers, where previously only the formulas for the sums of squares and cubes had been stated.
[src:diameter/alhazen] His method can be readily generalized to find the formula for the sum of any integral powers, although he did not himself do this (perhaps because he only needed the fourth power to calculate the volume of the paraboloid he was interested in).
[src:diameter/alhazen] He used his result on sums of integral powers to perform what would now be called an integration, where the formulas for the sums of integral squares and fourth powers allowed him to calculate the volume of a paraboloid.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen eventually solved the problem using conic sections and a geometric proof.
[src:diameter/alhazen] His solution was extremely long and complicated and may not have been understood by mathematicians reading him in Latin translation.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Later mathematicians used Descartes' analytical methods to analyse the problem.
[src:diameter/alhazen] An algebraic solution to the problem was finally found in 1965 by Jack M.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Other solutions were discovered in 1989, by Harald Riede and in 1997 by the Oxford mathematician Peter M.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Recently, Mitsubishi Electric Research Laboratories (MERL) researchers solved the extension of Alhazen's problem to general rotationally symmetric quadric mirrors including hyperbolic, parabolic and elliptical mirrors.
[src:diameter/alhazen] The camera obscura was known to the ancient Chinese, and was described by the Han Chinese polymath Shen Kuo in his scientific book *Dream Pool Essays*, published in the year 1088 C.E.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Aristotle had discussed the basic principle behind it in his *Problems*, but Alhazen's work contained the first clear description of camera obscura. and early analysis of the device.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Ibn al-Haytham used a camera obscura mainly to observe a partial solar eclipse.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In his essay, Ibn al-Haytham writes that he observed the sickle-like shape of the sun at the time of an eclipse.
[src:diameter/alhazen] It is admitted that his findings solidified the importance in the history of the camera obscura but this treatise is important in many other respects.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Ancient optics and medieval optics were divided into optics and burning mirrors.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Optics proper mainly focused on the study of vision, while burning mirrors focused on the properties of light and luminous rays.
[src:diameter/alhazen] *On the shape of the eclipse* is probably one of the first attempts made by Ibn al-Haytham to articulate these two sciences.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Very often Ibn al-Haytham's discoveries benefited from the intersection of mathematical and experimental contributions.
[src:diameter/alhazen] This is the case with *On the shape of the eclipse*.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Besides the fact that this treatise allowed more people to study partial eclipses of the sun, it especially allowed to better understand how the camera obscura works.
[src:diameter/alhazen] This treatise is a physico-mathematical study of image formation inside the camera obscura.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Ibn al-Haytham takes an experimental approach, and determines the result by varying the size and the shape of the aperture, the focal length of the camera, the shape and intensity of the light source.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In his work he explains the inversion of the image in the camera obscura, the fact that the image is similar to the source when the hole is small, but also the fact that the image can differ from the source when the hole is large.
[src:diameter/alhazen] All these results are produced by using a point analysis of the image.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In the seventh tract of his book of optics, Alhazen described an apparatus for experimenting with various cases of refraction, in order to investigate the relations between the angle of incidence, the angle of refraction and the angle of deflection.
[src:diameter/alhazen] This apparatus was a modified version of an apparatus used by Ptolemy for similar purpose.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen explained color constancy, the observation that objects are perceived having the same color under different types of illumination, in terms of perception in the visual system.
[src:diameter/alhazen] This explanation was an early form of the concept of unconscious inference, the idea that the visual system work involuntarily.
[src:diameter/alhazen] The *Kitab al-Manazir* (Book of Optics) describes several experimental observations that Alhazen made and how he used his results to explain certain optical phenomena using mechanical analogies.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He conducted experiments with projectiles and concluded that only the impact of perpendicular projectiles on surfaces was forceful enough to make them penetrate, whereas surfaces tended to deflect oblique projectile strikes.
[src:diameter/alhazen] For example, to explain refraction from a rare to a dense medium, he used the mechanical analogy of an iron ball thrown at a thin slate covering a wide hole in a metal sheet.
[src:diameter/alhazen] A perpendicular throw breaks the slate and passes through, whereas an oblique one with equal force and from an equal distance does not.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He also used this result to explain how intense, direct light hurts the eye, using a mechanical analogy: Alhazen associated 'strong' lights with perpendicular rays and 'weak' lights with oblique ones.
[src:diameter/alhazen] The obvious answer to the problem of multiple rays and the eye was in the choice of the perpendicular ray, since only one such ray from each point on the surface of the object could penetrate the eye.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Sudanese psychologist Omar Khaleefa has argued that Alhazen should be considered the founder of experimental psychology, for his pioneering work on the psychology of visual perception and optical illusions.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Khaleefa has also argued that Alhazen should also be considered the "founder of psychophysics", a sub-discipline and precursor to modern psychology.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Although Alhazen made many subjective reports regarding vision, there is no evidence that he used quantitative psychophysical techniques and the claim has been rebuffed.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen offered an explanation of the Moon illusion, an illusion that played an important role in the scientific tradition of medieval Europe.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Many authors repeated explanations that attempted to solve the problem of the Moon appearing larger near the horizon than it does when higher up in the sky.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen argued against Ptolemy's refraction theory, and defined the problem in terms of perceived, rather than real, enlargement.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He said that judging the distance of an object depends on there being an uninterrupted sequence of intervening bodies between the object and the observer.
[src:diameter/alhazen] When the Moon is high in the sky there are no intervening objects, so the Moon appears close.
[src:diameter/alhazen] The perceived size of an object of constant angular size varies with its perceived distance.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Therefore, the Moon appears closer and smaller high in the sky, and further and larger on the horizon.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Through works by Roger Bacon, John Pecham and Witelo based on Alhazen's explanation, the Moon illusion gradually came to be accepted as a psychological phenomenon, with the refraction theory being rejected in the 17th century.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Although Alhazen is often credited with the perceived distance explanation, he was not the first author to offer it.
[src:diameter/alhazen] 2nd century) gave this account (in addition to refraction), and he credited it to Posidonius (c.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Ptolemy may also have offered this explanation in his *Optics*, but the text is obscure.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen's writings were more widely available in the Middle Ages than those of these earlier authors, and that probably explains why Alhazen received the credit.
[src:diameter/alhazen] An aspect associated with Alhazen's optical research is related to systemic and methodological reliance on experimentation (*iḵtibār*) (Arabic: اختبار) and controlled testing in his scientific inquiries.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Moreover, his experimental directives rested on combining classical physics (*ilm tabi'i*) with mathematics (*ta'alim*; geometry in particular).
[src:diameter/alhazen] Toomer expressed some skepticism regarding Schramm's view, partly because at the time (1964) the *Book of Optics* had not yet been fully translated from Arabic, and Toomer was concerned that without context, specific passages might be read anachronistically.
[src:diameter/alhazen] While acknowledging Alhazen's importance in developing experimental techniques, Toomer argued that Alhazen should not be considered in isolation from other Islamic and ancient thinkers.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Toomer concluded his review by saying that it would not be possible to assess Schramm's claim that Ibn al-Haytham was the true founder of modern physics without translating more of Alhazen's work and fully investigating his influence on later medieval writers.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Besides the *Book of Optics*, Alhazen wrote several other treatises on the same subject, including his *Risala fi l-Daw'* (*Treatise on Light*).
[src:diameter/alhazen] He investigated the properties of luminance, the rainbow, eclipses, twilight, and moonlight.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Experiments with mirrors and the refractive interfaces between air, water, and glass cubes, hemispheres, and quarter-spheres provided the foundation for his theories on catoptrics.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He investigated the decrease in the intensity of light with the increase in distance, and there has even been speculation that he might have been aware of the inverse-square law of optics.
[src:diameter/alhazen] The suggestion of mechanical models for the Earth centred Ptolemaic model "greatly contributed to the eventual triumph of the Ptolemaic system among the Christians of the West".
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen's determination to root astronomy in the realm of physical objects was important, however, because it meant astronomical hypotheses "were accountable to the laws of physics", and could be criticised and improved upon in those terms.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He also wrote *Maqala fi daw al-qamar* (*On the Light of the Moon*).
[src:diameter/alhazen] In his work, Alhazen discussed theories on the motion of a body.
[src:diameter/alhazen] The book is a non-technical explanation of Ptolemy's *Almagest*, which was eventually translated into Hebrew and Latin in the 13th and 14th centuries and subsequently had an influence on astronomers such as Georg von Peuerbach during the European Middle Ages and Renaissance.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Ptolemy's *Almagest* concerned mathematical theories regarding the motion of the planets, whereas the *Hypotheses* concerned what Ptolemy thought was the actual configuration of the planets.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Ptolemy himself acknowledged that his theories and configurations did not always agree with each other, arguing that this was not a problem provided it did not result in noticeable error, but Alhazen was particularly scathing in his criticism of the inherent contradictions in Ptolemy's works.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Having pointed out the problems, Alhazen appears to have intended to resolve the contradictions he pointed out in Ptolemy in a later work.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen believed there was a "true configuration" of the planets that Ptolemy had failed to grasp.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He intended to complete and repair Ptolemy's system, not to replace it completely.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He held that the criticism of existing theories – which dominated this book – holds a special place in the growth of scientific knowledge.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen's *The Model of the Motions of Each of the Seven Planets* was written c.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Only one damaged manuscript has been found, with only the introduction and the first section, on the theory of planetary motion, surviving.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He kept a geocentric universe and assumed that celestial motions are uniformly circular, which required the inclusion of epicycles to explain observed motion, but he managed to eliminate Ptolemy's equant.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In general, his model did not try to provide a causal explanation of the motions, but concentrated on providing a complete, geometric description that could explain observed motions without the contradictions inherent in Ptolemy's model.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He concluded that the parallax is (probably very much) smaller than Lunar parallax, and the Milky way should be a celestial object.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Though he was not the first who argued that the Milky Way does not belong to the atmosphere, he is the first who did quantitative analysis for the claim.
[src:diameter/alhazen] The fourth group consists of ten works on astronomical theory, including the *Doubts* and *Model of the Motions* discussed above.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In mathematics, Alhazen built on the mathematical works of Euclid and Thabit ibn Qurra and worked on "the beginnings of the link between algebra and geometry".
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen made developments in conic sections and number theory.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He developed a formula for summing the first 100 natural numbers, using a geometric proof to prove the formula.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen explored what is now known as the Euclidean parallel postulate, the fifth postulate in Euclid's *Elements*, using a proof by contradiction, and in effect introducing the concept of motion into geometry.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He formulated the Lambert quadrilateral, which Boris Abramovich Rozenfeld names the "Ibn al-Haytham–Lambert quadrilateral".
[src:diameter/alhazen] He was criticised by Omar Khayyam who pointed that Aristotle had condemned the use of motion in geometry.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In elementary geometry, Alhazen attempted to solve the problem of squaring the circle using the area of lunes (crescent shapes), but later gave up on the impossible task.
[src:diameter/alhazen] The two lunes formed from a right triangle by erecting a semicircle on each of the triangle's sides, inward for the hypotenuse and outward for the other two sides, are known as the lunes of Alhazen; they have the same total area as the triangle itself.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen's contributions to number theory include his work on perfect numbers.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In his *Analysis and Synthesis*, he may have been the first to state that every even perfect number is of the form 2*n*−1(2*n* − 1) where 2*n* − 1 is prime, but he was not able to prove this result; Euler later proved it in the 18th century, and it is now called the Euclid–Euler theorem.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen solved problems involving congruences using what is now called Wilson's theorem.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In his *Opuscula*, Alhazen considers the solution of a system of congruences, and gives two general methods of solution.
[src:diameter/alhazen] His first method, the canonical method, involved Wilson's theorem, while his second method involved a version of the Chinese remainder theorem.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen discovered the sum formula for the fourth power, using a method that could be generally used to determine the sum for any integral power.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He used this to find the volume of a paraboloid.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He could find the integral formula for any polynomial without having developed a general formula.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen also wrote a *Treatise on the Influence of Melodies on the Souls of Animals*, although no copies have survived.
[src:diameter/alhazen] It appears to have been concerned with the question of whether animals could react to music, for example whether a camel would increase or decrease its pace.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In engineering, one account of his career as a civil engineer has him summoned to Egypt by the Fatimid Caliph, Al-Hakim bi-Amr Allah, to regulate the flooding of the Nile River.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He carried out a detailed scientific study of the annual inundation of the Nile River, and he drew plans for building a dam, at the site of the modern-day Aswan Dam.
[src:diameter/alhazen] His field work, however, later made him aware of the impracticality of this scheme, and he soon feigned madness so he could avoid punishment from the Caliph.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In his *Treatise on Place*, Alhazen disagreed with Aristotle's view that nature abhors a void, and he used geometry in an attempt to demonstrate that place (*al-makan*) is the imagined three-dimensional void between the inner surfaces of a containing body.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Abd-el-latif, a supporter of Aristotle's philosophical view of place, later criticized the work in *Fi al-Radd 'ala Ibn al-Haytham fi al-makan* (*A refutation of Ibn al-Haytham's place*) for its geometrization of place.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen also discussed space perception and its epistemological implications in his *Book of Optics*.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In "tying the visual perception of space to prior bodily experience, Alhazen unequivocally rejected the intuitiveness of spatial perception and, therefore, the autonomy of vision.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen was a Muslim and most sources report that he was a Sunni and a follower of the Ash'ari school.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Ziauddin Sardar says that some of the greatest Muslim scientists, such as Ibn al-Haytham and Abū Rayhān al-Bīrūnī, who were pioneers of the scientific method, were themselves followers of the Ashʿari school of Islamic theology.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen wrote a work on Islamic theology in which he discussed prophethood and developed a system of philosophical criteria to discern its false claimants in his time.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He also wrote a treatise entitled *Finding the Direction of Qibla by Calculation* in which he discussed finding the Qibla, where prayers (salat) are directed towards, mathematically.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen made significant contributions to optics, number theory, geometry, astronomy and natural philosophy.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen's work on optics is credited with contributing a new emphasis on experiment.
[src:diameter/alhazen] His main work, *Kitab al-Manazir* (*Book of Optics*), was known in the Muslim world mainly, but not exclusively, through the thirteenth-century commentary by Kamāl al-Dīn al-Fārisī, the *Tanqīḥ*al-Manāẓir*li-dhawī l-abṣār wa l-baṣā'ir*.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In al-Andalus, it was used by the eleventh-century prince of the Banu Hud dynasty of Zaragossa and author of an important mathematical text, al-Mu'taman ibn Hūd.
[src:diameter/alhazen] A Latin translation of the *Kitab al-Manazir* was made probably in the late twelfth or early thirteenth century.
[src:diameter/alhazen] This translation was read by and greatly influenced a number of scholars in Christian Europe including: Roger Bacon, Robert Grosseteste, Witelo, Giambattista della Porta, Leonardo da Vinci, Galileo Galilei, Christiaan Huygens, René Descartes, and Johannes Kepler.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Meanwhile, in the Islamic world, Alhazen's legacy was further advanced through the 'reforming' of his *Optics* by Persian scientist Kamal al-Din al-Farisi (died c.
[src:diameter/alhazen] 1320) in the latter's *Kitab Tanqih al-Manazir* (*The Revision of* [Ibn al-Haytham's] *Optics*).
[src:diameter/alhazen] Alhazen wrote as many as 200 books, although only 55 have survived.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Some of his treatises on optics survived only through Latin translation.
[src:diameter/alhazen] During the Middle Ages his books on cosmology were translated into Latin, Hebrew and other languages.
[src:diameter/alhazen] The impact crater Alhazen on the Moon is named in his honour, as was the asteroid 59239 Alhazen.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In honour of Alhazen, the Aga Khan University (Pakistan) named its Ophthalmology endowed chair as "The Ibn-e-Haitham Associate Professor and Chief of Ophthalmology".
[src:diameter/alhazen] The 2015 International Year of Light celebrated the 1000th anniversary of the works on optics by Ibn Al-Haytham.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In 2014, the "Hiding in the Light" episode of *Cosmos: A Spacetime Odyssey*, presented by Neil deGrasse Tyson, focused on the accomplishments of Ibn al-Haytham.
[src:diameter/alhazen] He was voiced by Alfred Molina in the episode.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Over forty years previously, Jacob Bronowski presented Alhazen's work in a similar television documentary (and the corresponding book), *The Ascent of Man*.
[src:diameter/alhazen] In episode 5 (*The Music of the Spheres*), Bronowski remarked that in his view, Alhazen was "the one really original scientific mind that Arab culture produced", whose theory of optics was not improved on till the time of Isaac Newton and Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz.
[src:diameter/alhazen] UNESCO declared 2015 the International Year of Light and its Director-General Irina Bokova dubbed Ibn al-Haytham 'the father of optics'.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Amongst others, this was to celebrate Ibn Al-Haytham's achievements in optics, mathematics and astronomy.
[src:diameter/alhazen] The campaign also produced and released the short educational film 1001 Inventions and the World of Ibn Al-Haytham.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Ibn al-Haytham appears on the 10,000 dinar banknote of the Iraqi dinar, series 2003.
[src:diameter/alhazen] According to medieval biographers, Alhazen wrote more than 200 works on a wide range of subjects, of which at least 96 of his scientific works are known.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Most of his works are now lost, but more than 50 of them have survived to some extent.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Nearly half of his surviving works are on mathematics, 23 of them are on astronomy, and 14 of them are on optics, with a few on other subjects.
[src:diameter/alhazen] Not all his surviving works have yet been studied, but some of the ones that have are given below.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] In geometry, an **altitude** of a triangle is a line segment through a given vertex (called *apex*) and perpendicular to a line containing the side or edge opposite the apex.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] This (finite) edge and (infinite) line extension are called, respectively, the *base* and *extended base* of the altitude.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] The point at the intersection of the extended base and the altitude is called the ***foot*** of the altitude.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] The length of the altitude, often simply called "the altitude" or "height", symbol h, is the distance between the foot and the apex.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] The process of drawing the altitude from a vertex to the foot is known as *dropping the altitude* at that vertex.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] It is a special case of orthogonal projection.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] Altitudes can be used in the computation of the area of a triangle: one-half of the product of an altitude's length and its base's length (symbol b) equals the triangle's area: A=hb/2.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] Thus, the longest altitude is perpendicular to the shortest side of the triangle.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] The altitudes are also related to the sides of the triangle through the trigonometric functions.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] In an isosceles triangle (a triangle with two congruent sides), the altitude having the incongruent side as its base will have the midpoint of that side as its foot.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] Also the altitude having the incongruent side as its base will be the angle bisector of the vertex angle.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] In a right triangle, the altitude drawn to the hypotenuse c divides the hypotenuse into two segments of lengths p and q.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] For acute triangles, the feet of the altitudes all fall on the triangle's sides (not extended).
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] In an obtuse triangle (one with an obtuse angle), the foot of the altitude to the obtuse-angled vertex falls in the interior of the opposite side, but the feet of the altitudes to the acute-angled vertices fall on the opposite extended side, exterior to the triangle.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] This is illustrated in the adjacent diagram: in this obtuse triangle, an altitude dropped perpendicularly from the top vertex, which has an acute angle, intersects the extended horizontal side outside the triangle.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] The geometric altitude figures prominently in many important theorems and their proofs.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] For example, besides those theorems listed below, the altitude plays a central role in proofs of both the Law of sines and Law of cosines.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] The orthocenter of a triangle, usually denoted by H, is the point where the three (possibly extended) altitudes intersect.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] The orthocenter lies inside the triangle if and only if the triangle is acute.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] For a right triangle, the orthocenter coincides with the vertex at the right angle.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] For an equilateral triangle, all triangle centers (including the orthocenter) coincide at its centroid.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] This follows from combining Heron's formula for the area of a triangle in terms of the sides with the area formula ${\tfrac {1}{2}}\times {\text{base}}\times {\text{height}},$ where the base is taken as side a and the height is the altitude from the vertex A (opposite side a).
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] By exchanging the a on the denominator with b or c, this equation can also used to find the altitudes hb and hc, respectively.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] Any two altitudes of a triangle are inversely proportional with the sides on which they fall.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] Consider an arbitrary triangle with sides a, b, c and with corresponding altitudes ha, hb, hc.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] From any point P within an equilateral triangle, the sum of the perpendiculars to the three sides is equal to the altitude of the triangle.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] In a right triangle with legs a and b and hypotenuse c, each of the legs is also an altitude: ⁠ $h_{a}=b$ ⁠ and ⁠ $h_{b}=a$ ⁠.
[src:diameter/altitude-triangle] This is also known as the inverse Pythagorean theorem.
[src:diameter/diameter] In geometry, a **diameter** of a circle is any straight line segment that passes through the centre of the circle and whose endpoints lie on the circle.
[src:diameter/diameter] It can also be defined as the longest chord of the circle.
[src:diameter/diameter] Both definitions are also valid for the diameter of a sphere.
[src:diameter/diameter] In more modern usage, the length d of a diameter is also called the diameter.
[src:diameter/diameter] The word "diameter" is derived from Ancient Greek διάμετρος*(*diametros*)* 'diameter of a circle', from διά*(*dia*)* 'across, through' and μέτρον*(*metron*)* 'measure'.
[src:diameter/diameter] With straightedge and compass, a diameter of a given circle can be constructed as the perpendicular bisector of an arbitrary chord.
[src:diameter/diameter] Drawing two diameters in this way can be used to locate the center of a circle, as their crossing point.
[src:diameter/diameter] To construct a diameter parallel to a given line, choose the chord to be perpendicular to the line.
[src:diameter/diameter] The circle having a given line segment as its diameter can be constructed by straightedge and compass, by finding the midpoint of the segment and then drawing the circle centered at the midpoint through one of the ends of the line segment.
[src:diameter/diameter] The symbol or variable for diameter, ⌀, is sometimes used in technical drawings or specifications as a prefix or suffix for a number (e.g.
[src:diameter/diameter] "⌀ 55 mm"), indicating that it represents diameter.
[src:diameter/diameter] Photographic filter thread sizes are often denoted in this way.
[src:diameter/diameter] The symbol has a code point in Unicode at U+2300 ⌀ DIAMETER SIGN, in the Miscellaneous Technical set.
[src:diameter/diameter] It should not be confused with several other characters (such as U+00D8 Ø LATIN CAPITAL LETTER O WITH STROKE or U+2205 ∅ EMPTY SET) that resemble it but have unrelated meanings.
[src:diameter/diameter] The definitions given above are only valid for circles and spheres.
[src:diameter/diameter] However, they are special cases of a more general definition that is valid for any kind of n -dimensional object, or a set of scattered points.
[src:diameter/diameter] The *diameter of a set* is the least upper bound of the set of all distances between pairs of points in the subset.
[src:diameter/diameter] A different and incompatible definition is sometimes used for the diameter of a conic section.
[src:diameter/diameter] In this context, a diameter is any chord which passes through the conic's centre.
[src:diameter/diameter] A diameter of an ellipse is any line passing through the centre of the ellipse.
[src:diameter/diameter] Half of any such diameter may be called a ***semidiameter***, although this term is most often a synonym for the radius of a circle or sphere.
[src:diameter/diameter] The longest and shortest diameters are called the *major axis* and *minor axis*, respectively.
[src:diameter/diameter] *Conjugate diameters* are a pair of diameters where one is parallel to a tangent to the ellipse at the endpoint of the other diameter.
[src:diameter/diameter] Several kinds of object can be measured by *equivalent diameter*, the diameter of a circular or spherical approximation to the object.
[src:diameter/diameter] This includes hydraulic diameter, the equivalent diameter of a channel or pipe through which liquid flows, and the Sauter mean diameter of a collection of particles.
[src:diameter/diameter] The diameter of a circle is exactly twice its radius.
[src:diameter/diameter] However, this is true only for a circle, and only in the Euclidean metric.
[src:diameter/diameter] Jung's theorem provides more general inequalities relating the diameter to the radius.
